    "recap_headline": "",
    "recap_text": "HUNTSVILLE \u2013\nSam Houston scored three times to take the lead in the bottom of the eighth inning, but Jax State rallied with two scores in the top of the ninth to pick up a 4-3 win over the Bearkats and complete a series sweep on Sunday at Don Sanders Stadium.\nSam Houston (8-11, 0-3 CUSA) got a career-best start from\nTate Hickman\n, but again saw its offense slow to get going against Gamecock (17-3, 3-0 CUSA) starting pitching as JSU ran its win streak to seven games in a row.\nHickman went a career-long 5.0 innings in the start and struck out five JSU hitters without a walk. He allowed a pair of runs in the second inning, but nothing else and got taken off the hook for the loss with the Kats' rally in the eighth.\nJSU starter Steven Cash gave the Kats a\u00a0tough\u00a0time, striking out five and allowing just two hits in 6.0 shutout\u00a0innings\u00a0of his start, retiring 11 of the first 12 hitters he faced while getting staked with a 2-0 lead with a\u00a0pair of Gamecock runs in the second.\nThe Kats still\u00a0trailed 2-0 going into the bottom of the eighth but put two runners on base with just one out and\nSean Bazmore\ndelivered a pinch-hit, RBI single to cut the lead to 2-1. A walk to\nRyan Franden\nthen loaded the bases for\nHunter Alvord\nwho put the ball in play and beat out a double-play grounder that was compounded by a JSU error which allowed two runs to score and Sam Houston to take a 3-2 lead.\nBut the Kats immediately put themselves in hot water in the ninth by hitting the leadoff man and walking the next, setting the table for the Gamecocks to re-take the lead on an RBI grounder by Jaxon Pate and an RBI single from Trey King.\nSam Houston threatened in the bottom of the inning, getting the tying run to second base with nobody out; however, Jax State stopper Skyler Hutto left the runner there with outs of the final three hitters of the game to earn the win in relief.\nSam Houston had just five hits in the game, all singles, with two coming from\nNathan Fink\n. Hickman took a no-decision on the mound, while\nJonathan Anders\ncontinued to show well this year with 2.1 strong innings of relief.\nKade Neuenschwander\nwas the tough-luck loser, allowing the go-ahead run in the ninth to fall to 0-2 on the year.\nUP NEXT\nThe Kats have a busy week coming up with a midweek game at Lamar set for Tuesday and a 3-game series at FIU on the slate for the weekend. All games can be watched on ESPN+."
  },
